# Oracle Fusion Architecture Agent Context

## Purpose

This document defines the **high-level architecture model of Oracle
Fusion HCM + ERP** for use by an AI agent.

The goal is to allow the agent to explain the Oracle Fusion ecosystem,
system relationships, and process flows **at a glance**.

The agent should treat the platform as a **layered enterprise system**
rather than a collection of unrelated modules.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Core System Principle

Oracle Fusion operates as a pipeline:

Capture Work ↓ Validate Rules ↓ Calculate Outcomes ↓ Route to Accounting
↓ Record Financial Truth ↓ Report Results

Every module in the platform participates in this pipeline.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Architecture Layers

The Oracle Fusion ecosystem can be understood as **seven architectural
layers**.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 1. Experience Layer

This layer represents how users interact with the system.

### Users

-   Employees
-   Managers
-   HR Administrators
-   Payroll Administrators
-   Finance Users
-   Procurement Users
-   Executives

### Interfaces

-   Redwood UI
-   Self Service
-   Manager Work Areas
-   HR Work Areas
-   Finance Work Areas
-   Dashboards
-   Approvals

Purpose: Capture user actions and initiate business transactions.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 2. Operational Domain Layer

This layer contains the major application domains.

### HCM Domain

Modules:

-   Core HR
-   Recruiting
-   Workforce Structures
-   Time and Labor
-   Absence Management
-   Benefits
-   Payroll
-   Talent Management

Purpose: Manage the workforce lifecycle.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### ERP Domain

Modules:

-   General Ledger
-   Accounts Payable
-   Accounts Receivable
-   Procurement
-   Cash Management
-   Fixed Assets
-   Projects
-   Grants
-   Budgetary Control

Purpose: Manage financial and operational transactions.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 3. Processing and Control Layer

This layer determines how transactions behave.

### Business Logic

Examples:

-   Fast Formulas
-   Time Rules
-   Eligibility Profiles
-   Payroll Rules
-   Approval Workflows
-   Funds Check
-   Encumbrance Accounting
-   Subledger Accounting Rules

Purpose: Validate, calculate, and route transactions.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Security and Governance

Security model includes:

-   Job Roles
-   Duty Roles
-   Data Roles
-   Security Profiles
-   Data Access Policies
-   Approval Policies

Purpose: Control access and enforce governance.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 4. Shared Enterprise Foundation

This layer provides structural context for all transactions.

### Enterprise Structures

Core objects:

-   Legal Entities
-   Ledgers
-   Business Units
-   Departments / Cost Centers
-   Organizations
-   Jobs
-   Positions

Purpose: Define the organizational structure of the enterprise.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Shared Configuration

Shared configuration objects include:

-   Value Sets
-   Lookups
-   Flexfields
-   Reference Data Sets
-   Document Sequences
-   Enterprise Calendar
-   Currency Setup

Purpose: Provide reusable configuration across modules.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 5. Accounting and Financial Truth Layer

This layer records the financial impact of transactions.

Core components:

-   Payroll Costing
-   Financial Distributions
-   Subledger Accounting
-   Journal Creation
-   General Ledger
-   Audit Trail

Purpose: Create the official financial record of the organization.

All operational activity ultimately posts to the **General Ledger**.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 6. Data and Reporting Layer

This layer exposes system data.

Components:

-   OTBI (Operational Transactional BI)
-   BI Publisher
-   Fusion Analytics Warehouse
-   Financial Statements
-   Operational Reports
-   Data Extracts

Purpose: Provide insight and reporting across the system.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 7. Integration and Platform Layer

This layer connects Fusion to the outside world.

### Integration Tools

-   REST APIs
-   HDL (HCM Data Loader)
-   HSDL
-   FBDI
-   Oracle Integration Cloud

### External Systems

Examples:

-   Banks
-   State Government Systems
-   Tax Agencies
-   Pension Systems
-   Data Warehouses

Purpose: Move data between systems.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Core Enterprise Flows

The following flows represent common end-to-end system processes.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Hire to Retire

Recruit Candidate ↓ Hire Worker ↓ Create Assignment ↓ Workforce
Management ↓ Payroll ↓ Financial Accounting ↓ Reporting

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Time to Payroll

Employee enters time ↓ Time validation rules ↓ Time Consumer Set ↓
Payroll calculation ↓ Payroll costing ↓ Subledger accounting ↓ General
ledger

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Procure to Pay

Requisition ↓ Approval ↓ Purchase Order ↓ Funds Check ↓ Receipt ↓
Invoice ↓ Payment ↓ Accounting ↓ General Ledger

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Budget to Actual

Budget Creation ↓ Control Budget ↓ Funds Reservation ↓ Encumbrance ↓
Expenditure ↓ Budget Consumption ↓ Budget vs Actual Reporting

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# System Mental Model

The agent should understand that Oracle Fusion behaves as a
**transaction processing pipeline**.

User Action ↓ Application Module ↓ Validation Rules ↓ Enterprise
Structure Context ↓ Accounting Engine ↓ Reporting ↓ External Systems

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# How the Agent Should Respond

When explaining a concept, the agent should always include:

1.  The architecture layer
2.  The module domain
3.  The upstream process
4.  The downstream impact

Example:

Component: Payroll Costing

Layer: Accounting Layer

Purpose: Allocates payroll results to financial accounting
distributions.

Upstream: Payroll Run

Downstream: Subledger Accounting → General Ledger

------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Architecture Summary

Oracle Fusion can be summarized as the following stack:

Users ↓ Experience ↓ HCM and ERP Domains ↓ Rules and Controls ↓
Enterprise Structures ↓ Accounting Engine ↓ Reporting ↓ Integrations ↓
Platform
